<h2>Copyright: You as Consumer</h2>

<p>
As a consumer, you basically cannot legally do the following if you do not own the copyright on a work:
</p>

<ol>
<li><strong>Copy the work.</strong> This means online media too, like images, music, etc.</li>
<li><strong>Create derivative work or collect money from derivative work.</strong></li>
<li><strong>Distribute copies of the work.</strong> This means, for example, you can't burn a bunch of CDs and sell them or give them away.</li>
<li><strong>Perform someone else's original work in public without getting permission and/or paying a royalty.</strong> Unless you want to pay to perform something, it's safer to stick with your own original material.</li>
<li><strong>Display the work in public.</strong></li>
</ol>

<p class="citation">
(<a href="JavaScript:Citation('0011');">17 USC 106, 2002</a>)
</p>

